The paper discusses the phenomenon of double descent in deep neural networks, which is a topic closely related to machine learning and artificial intelligence. Specifically, the paper focuses on the lazy learning regime of neural networks, which is a subfield of machine learning concerned with learning high-dimensional functions with random features regression. Therefore, cs.LG (Machine Learning) and cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) are the most likely sub-categories. Additionally, the paper presents numerical experiments on classic deep learning setups, which involve computer vision (cs.CV) and natural language processing (cs.NE). Finally, the paper also discusses the bias-variance trade-off, which is a topic in information theory (cs.IT).
